SIMPLE: interpolation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interpolation
<hw>In*ter`po*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>interpolatio</ets> an alteration made here and there: cf. F.
<ets>interpolation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of introducing
or inserting anything, especially that which is spurious or
foreign.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is introduced or inserted, especially
something foreign or spurious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bentley wrote a letter . . . . upon the scriptural glosses in our
present copies of Hesychius, which he considered
<qex>interpolations</qex> from a later hand.</q> <rj><qau>De
Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>The method or operation of
finding from a few given terms of a series, as of numbers or
observations, other intermediate terms in conformity with the law of the
series.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interpolator</ent>⟦br⟧
